f=Engineering/dana/custom/datastore-selection/SKILL.md · in=datastore-selection dana's choice discipline: matching data access patterns right store relational, document, key-value, graph, vector instead forcing everything one team already knows. carries HelixDB playbook because graph+vector exactly shape agent/RAG/memory workloads want, because HelixDB live candidate toongine's memory layer platform-level ADR flagged plan). · p=wrong datastore slow, expensive mistake reverse. relational store bent graph traversal, vector search bolted onto SQL table, produces N+1 queries latency cliffs scale badly. Choosing access pattern recording choice ADR puts right shape under data start. · wu=Triggers: "which database," "relational graph," "do need vector store," "how store this," new data domain, RAG/embedding/memory workloads, toongine-memory platform decision. · st:/ Protocol=`A data domain to store \· -> Characterize: access patterns (point lookup / range / join-heavy / traversal / similarity) \· \· consistency needs \· scale \· relationships (shallow vs deep/recursive) \· vector/semantic need \· -> Match to paradigm: \· relational (joins, transactions, known schema) \· document (flexible/nested) \·` · in=**Access pattern decides paradigm.** Point lookups want KV; joins transactions want relational; deep/recursive relationships want graph; similarity/embeddings want vector; agent-memory RAG-with-relationships want graph+vector together (the HelixDB case). Start data read written, familiar tool. **Don't multiply stores without cause.** datastore operational surface (backups, monitoring, expertise ops's burden). second store earn place against cost (dev's boring-is-a-feature). One well-chosen store beats three convenient ones. **Graph+vector HelixDB playbook.** workload agent memory, RAG, knowledge relationships, consult `assets/helixdb-playbook.md` (HelixQL, graph+vector native, toongine-memory candidacy). It's dated volatility split (ops's platform-playbooks pattern) HelixDB shipped Feb 2025 moves fast. **The choice ADR.** Datastore selection expensive reverse, it's dev architecture-decision: two options weighed their access-pattern fit, consequences honest. adoption updates stack-profile; drift (code using unlisted store) finding. **toongine memory platform ADR.** Whether toongine's graph-memory layer uses HelixDB platform-level decision dana co-authors dev flagged plan, decided ADR marcus/board carries strategic/spend weight. **Selection never runs migration.** Choosing store design; standing moving data migration-discipline, dana writes scripts operator executes them (Rail 3). two deliberately separate. · of=`## Datastore Selection: [domain] \· Access patterns: [lookup/range/join/traversal/similarity] \· consistency: [ ] \· scale: [ ] \· relationships: [ ] \· Options: [paradigm A — fit/cost] \· [paradigm B — fit/cost] \· Choice: [store] → dev ADR [ref] → stack-profile update \· Graph+vector? → HelixDB playbook [ref] \· toongine-memory relevance: [yes/no → platform ADR]` · pr=**Access pattern chooses paradigm** familiar tool., **Don't multiply stores without cause** operational burden earned., **Graph+vector workloads get HelixDB playbook** dated, volatility split., **Selection ADR** expensive reverse, recorded options consequences., **toongine memory platform ADR** co-authored dev, board carries weight., **Selecting migrating** design here; data movement migration-discipline under Rail · f=Access pattern unclear/early start relational (well-understood, flexible) unless clear graph/vector need exists; label provisional; revisit patterns emerge (don't prematurely adopt exotic stores)., HelixDB playbook stale (fast-moving project) dated playbook flags staleness; verify current HelixQL/features before committing (platform-playbooks discipline)., Multi-store genuinely needed document store's boundary sync/consistency story explicitly; seams data bugs live. · b:with Other Skills=**dev/architecture-decisions**: datastore choices ADRs; dev's stack-profile records adopted store., **data-modeling** (sibling) designs schema WITHIN chosen store; chooses store., **migration-discipline** (sibling) stands store moves data Rail operator-run., **db-performance** (sibling): chosen store's indexing/query tuning., **axiom**: storage data-structure complexity (its DSA records) informs graph/index choices here., **ops**: store adopted backup/monitoring/expiry surface maintenance-hygiene.